                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d731">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/9290: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-02-17T10:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 17, 1922—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>29. Following from Vladivostok:</p>
                <p>“February 16, 6 p.m. Kappel troops<note n="68" xml:id="d731fn68">White Russians,
                        taking their name from Gen. V. O. Kappel of the Siberian Army, who died in
                        January 1920 in the retreat following the defeat of Kolchak.</note> 12th
                    forced to retire before Red forces from Habarovsk have taken position at River
                    Amur. Japanese Army apparently much concerned report 10,000 Red against 4,000
                    White troops. If forced to retire through the, Japanese zone of operation
                    Kappels will undoubtedly be disarmed.[”]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
